{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14916"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14916"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.71,0.06,0.23,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7604"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14916"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44756"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5444"},{"type":"tags","id":"10803"},{"type":"tags","id":"10879"},{"type":"tags","id":"10909"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for advice about travel vaccinations before an extended trip to South America. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is concerned about various infectious diseases she may encounter. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathogens is most effectively controlled by acquired immunity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Protozoan parasites","Viruses","Prions","Bacterial endotoxins","Heat shock proteins"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adaptive or acquired immune system is particularly effective against intracellular pathogens, with \u003Cstrong\u003Eviruses\u003C/strong\u003E being the classic example. Viral infections trigger both humoral (antibody-mediated) and cellular immune responses, leading to the development of memory cells that provide long-lasting immunity. This is why vaccination against viral diseases can be so effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtozoan parasites\u003C/strong\u003E can be controlled by acquired immunity, but they often employ various evasion strategies such as antigenic variation that make immune responses less effective. Examples include \u003Cem\u003EPlasmodium\u003C/em\u003E species and \u003Cem\u003ETrypanosoma\u003C/em\u003E species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrions\u003C/strong\u003E are misfolded proteins that do not trigger classical immune responses as they are not recognised as foreign by the immune system. They are not effectively controlled by either innate or acquired immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial endotoxins\u003C/strong\u003E primarily trigger innate immune responses through pattern recognition receptors. While antibodies can be produced against some bacterial components, endotoxins themselves are primarily dealt with by the innate immune system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeat shock proteins\u003C/strong\u003E are highly conserved cellular proteins that can act as danger signals but are not primary targets of acquired immunity. They are actually involved in helping to initiate immune responses rather than being targets of them.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acquired immunity provides protection against multiple pathogens including bacteria, viruses, fungi, and protozoa through both humoral and cell-mediated responses.","Memory B and T cells enable a rapid immune response upon subsequent exposure to previously encountered pathogens.","The adaptive immune system can distinguish between self and non-self antigens to mount targeted responses."],"references":["Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002. Chapter 24, The Adaptive Immune System. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21070/","Marshall JS, Warrington R, Watson W, Kim HL. An introduction to immunology and immunopathology. Allergy Asthma Clin Immunol. 2018 Sep 12;14(Suppl 2):49. doi: 10.1186/s13223-018-0278-1. PMID: 30263032; PMCID: PMC6156898."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44756"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14916"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44756"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T10:50:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:56:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7604"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"